# Review Branch Workflow

## When to Use

Invoke this rule when reviewing a branch, pull request, or code changes.

## Review Steps

### 1. Understand the Context

- Read the PR description and linked ticket/issue
- Understand what problem is being solved
- Note the expected behavior and acceptance criteria

### 2. Check Out the Branch

```bash
# Fetch latest changes
git fetch origin

# Check out the branch to review
git checkout <branch-name>

# Install dependencies if changed
npm install
```

### 3. Run the Application

```bash
# Start the dev server
npm run dev

# Run tests
npm test

# Check for lint errors
npm run lint
```

### 4. Code Review Checklist

#### Functionality
- [ ] Code works as described in the PR
- [ ] Edge cases are handled
- [ ] Error states are handled gracefully
- [ ] No regressions in existing functionality

#### Code Quality
- [ ] Code follows project conventions
- [ ] No `any` types or type assertions
- [ ] No hard-coded values that should be configurable
- [ ] No console.log statements left in
- [ ] No commented-out code
- [ ] DRY principle followed (no unnecessary duplication)

#### React Patterns
- [ ] Components are focused and single-purpose
- [ ] State is kept as local as possible
- [ ] API calls use TanStack Query
- [ ] No unnecessary useEffect hooks
- [ ] Proper loading and error states

#### Styling
- [ ] Uses CSS Modules or theme system
- [ ] No hard-coded colors or font sizes
- [ ] Responsive design works on mobile/tablet/desktop
- [ ] Consistent spacing

#### Accessibility
- [ ] Images have alt text
- [ ] Form inputs have labels
- [ ] Interactive elements are keyboard accessible
- [ ] Sufficient color contrast

#### Testing
- [ ] Tests cover the main functionality
- [ ] Tests cover edge cases
- [ ] Tests are meaningful (not just for coverage)

### 5. Provide Feedback

When leaving comments:
- Be specific about the issue
- Explain why it's a problem
- Suggest a solution when possible
- Use "nit:" prefix for minor suggestions
- Distinguish between blocking issues and nice-to-haves

### 6. Approval Criteria

Approve when:
- All blocking issues are resolved
- Tests pass
- Code meets quality standards
- Functionality matches requirements
